{"product_id": "12120", "page": 945, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-30", "text": "Much like Vice City was to GTAIII, San Andreas improves on Vice City in every way.  New story, new characters, new settings, a hell of a lot of new vehicles, a playable world that is easily twice the size of Vice City, and much more.  The addition of RPG-like character stats is a change that is debatably good or bad, but San Andreas is probably the pinnacle of what GTA was always supposed to represent before the engine went super-realistic in GTA IV, and critics started getting paid to give stellar reviews.", "hours": 0.1, "username": "angrysquare", "products": 503, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "12120", "page": 946, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2012-12-30", "text": "Grand Theft Auto San Andreas is what I consider the best of the series. I am constantly surprised Rockstar managed to put this game on the PS2. It features a massive open world, with a simply sublime soundtrack and cast of characters. The gameplay was far more dynamic then it's predecessor. With being able to climb walls, to having a parachute, to finding a jetpack and doing drive by shootings from 50 feet in the air.\nSan Andreas was just as amazing when it first came out as it is today. Almost every modern sandbox game takes leaps and bounds that Rockstar first carved in 2004. If you only buy one Grand Theft Auto game, buy this one. You will definately not regret, nor forget, San Andreas.", "hours": 63.4, "username": "Silly/byte/", "products": 585, "early_access": false}
